article.headline: Charlotte holds onto second place in East
article.linkText: Liberty loses ninth consecutive road game
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Rushia Brown scored 14 points, and Andrea
Stinson added 13 as the Charlotte Sting pulled away to beat the New
York Liberty 65-54 Thursday night.

Brown, who had just two points in the past two games, helped
Charlotte (15-12) retain sole possession of second place in the
WNBA's Eastern Conference.

Dawn Staley added 12 points for the Sting.

Vickie Johnson scored 16 points, Tari Phillips 13 and Tamika
Whitmore 12 for New York (11-14), which lost its ninth straight
road game and fell to sixth place in the East.

Brown scored on a post move with 3:04 left to stop a Liberty
rally and keep Charlotte ahead 54-46.

Charlotte went on a 12-2 run in the second half to take a 47-37
lead, highlighted by Tammy Sutton-Brown's three-point play.

The Liberty committed 15 turnovers and were outrebounded 33-20
while seeing their two-game winning streak snapped.

In the first half, New York went nearly six minutes without
scoring while the Sting reeled off 10 straight points to take a
19-11 lead with 5:27 remaining. The teams combined to miss 38 of
their first 53 shots as Charlotte led 23-17 at the break.

The Liberty scored 17 points in the first 5:29 of the second
half and took a 34-31 lead on Johnson's 3-pointer.
